<h2>Stump Grinding: An Extra Cost to Plan For</h2>

<p>Tree removal usually does not include the stump. Most companies charge separately for <a href="/stump-grinding/">stump grinding</a>, which typically runs $100 to $400 in Concord depending on the stump diameter and root spread.</p>

<p>Grinding takes the stump down 6 to 12 inches below grade. The hole gets filled with the wood chips, and within a season your lawn grows over the spot. If you skip grinding, the stump attracts termites and carpenter ants, and new shoots will sprout from the roots for years.</p>

<p>Ask your tree service if they offer a bundled price for removal plus grinding. Most will knock $50 to $100 off the stump grinding cost when done alongside the removal.</p>

<h2>Does Tree Trimming Cost Less Than Removal?</h2>

<p>Yes, significantly. <a href="/tree-trimming/">Tree trimming and pruning</a> in Concord runs $150 to $1,200 depending on tree size and how much work is needed. Trimming preserves the tree while removing problem branches.</p>

<p>If your tree is healthy but has branches scraping your roof, hanging over a driveway, or blocking sunlight, trimming is the more affordable option. Not sure which service you need? Read our guide: <a href="/blog/tree-trimming-vs-tree-removal-which-do-you-need/">What's the Difference Between Tree Trimming and Tree Removal?</a></p>

<h2>How to Save on Tree Removal in Concord</h2>

<p>There are a few ways to get the most value:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Get three quotes.</strong> Prices vary widely between companies. Getting multiple estimates ensures you are paying a fair rate. <a href="/blog/how-to-hire-tree-removal-service-questions-to-ask/">Here is what to ask each company.</a></li>
  <li><strong>Schedule in late fall or winter.</strong> The dormant season (November through February) is slower for tree companies. Many offer lower rates during this period.</li>
  <li><strong>Bundle multiple trees.</strong> Removing two or three trees at once is almost always cheaper per tree than separate visits.</li>
  <li><strong>Keep the wood.</strong> If you have a fireplace or fire pit, ask the crew to leave the firewood-length logs. Hauling is a cost for the company, so offering to keep the wood can shave a bit off the price.</li>
  <li><strong>Check your homeowner's insurance.</strong> If a tree fell due to a storm or is threatening your home, your insurance may cover part or all of the removal cost. Call your adjuster before you call the tree service.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Do You Need a Permit in Concord?</h2>

<p>Concord does not require permits for removing trees on private residential property in most cases. However, if your property falls within a historic district or has specific HOA covenants, you may need approval before removing certain trees. If your tree is near a property line, talk to your neighbor first to avoid disputes.</p>

<p>When trees are near power lines, do not attempt removal yourself. Call your tree service and they will coordinate with Duke Energy if needed.</p>

